\cf0 \strokec2 Great question and good thinking that concern about confounding is somewhat different for post-only cross sectional study designs versus DiD study designs.\
For post-only cross sectional study designs any difference in baseline covariates where the covariate is also related to the level the outcome takes in the post period will create bias (is a confounder).\
For a DiD study design any difference in baseline covariates - or change in those covariates over time - that is also related to the change over time in the outcome will create bias. One way this can happen is that a baseline covariate that is related to the outcome level changes over time differently in the treated and non-treated groups leading to a different changes in the outcome that is not caused by the treatment. Another way this can happen is that differences in a baseline covariate that persist over time (but don't change) are related to how the outcome changes over time. For instance, in Lab 3, there was a big difference (10 percentage points) between countries where the leader was assassinated versus survived in whether countries were having a civil war before the assassination attempt. Having a civil war seems likely to be related to not just the level of a country's polity but to change in a country's polity over time.\
